00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:55.210
I think I can take
a couple questions

00:40:55.210 --> 00:40:58.000
if anyone has a question
about Lincoln.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:40:59.300
Sir?

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:00.790
&gt;&gt; Can you hear me?

00:41:00.790 --> 00:41:02.090
&gt;&gt; Sidney Blumenthal: Yes.

00:41:02.090 --> 00:41:05.960
&gt;&gt; I say this with humility, as you
know there are more books written

00:41:05.960 --> 00:41:08.800
about Lincoln than anything else.

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:13.390
What lead you to believe that
you would be able to add to this

00:41:13.390 --> 00:41:17.820
and what you just said, what
has not been known previously

00:41:17.820 --> 00:41:19.260
by other authors?

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:21.060
&gt;&gt; Sidney Blumenthal: Thank
you for that question.

00:41:21.060 --> 00:41:29.710 position:56%
When I fell down this rabbit hole of
Abraham Lincoln, I had no idea when

00:41:29.710 --> 00:41:33.830 position:56%
or how I would emerge and I am
still down this rabbit hole writing.

00:41:33.830 --> 00:41:39.340
But I thought that what I had
to offer was my own experience

00:41:39.340 --> 00:41:48.200
as a journalist, as somebody
who understood Washington,

00:41:48.200 --> 00:41:50.860
as somebody who grew up in
Illinois whose family is involved

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:55.170 position:56%
in Illinois politics and as somebody
who worked in the White House

00:41:55.170 --> 00:42:01.980
and participated in and
observed a presidency first hand.

00:42:01.980 --> 00:42:06.030
And so I thought that my
skills might be brought to bear

00:42:06.030 --> 00:42:10.830
to provide some original insight
and interpretation on Lincoln.

00:42:10.830 --> 00:42:15.440
And I hope I have done so
in the first two volumes

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:18.430
and in the next two to come,

00:42:18.430 --> 00:42:27.650
particularly about the house
divided, country torn apart

00:42:27.650 --> 00:42:31.240
and the emergence of
Lincoln's political leadership

00:42:31.240 --> 00:42:37.020
and how he dealt with that and
how he developed his argument

00:42:37.020 --> 00:42:42.810 position:56%
and his words and where he took it
from because he was only one person.

00:42:42.810 --> 00:42:48.550
And how he managed to
develop and find the means

00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:55.120
that eventually would save the
country and lead to emancipation.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:43:04.460
&gt;&gt; What was the Whigs Party, what
were their views on immigration?

00:43:04.460 --> 00:43:10.530
&gt;&gt; Sidney Blumenthal: Well,
there were no laws on immigration

00:43:10.530 --> 00:43:11.860
in the United States at the time.

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:14.630
The question was what were
the views on immigration?

00:43:14.630 --> 00:43:18.540
There were no laws
against immigration.

00:43:18.540 --> 00:43:21.530
People just came into the country.

00:43:21.530 --> 00:43:25.920 position:56%
But there was a lot of prejudice
against this new wave of immigration

00:43:25.920 --> 00:43:29.250
of the Irish and the
Germans particularly.

00:43:29.250 --> 00:43:30.950
And this movement developed
against it.

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:37.680
Lincoln, as I noted, abhorred
the Know-Nothing movement.

00:43:37.680 --> 00:43:41.120
But he only did so in private.

00:43:41.120 --> 00:43:46.980
And he operated behind the scenes
believing that it had to be undone

00:43:46.980 --> 00:43:51.760
by political means through
the operation of his friends.

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:53.980
And Lincoln did work
behind the scenes

00:43:53.980 --> 00:44:01.040
to undermine the Know-Nothing
movement, engaged in even methods

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:06.050
that we are familiar with
today in places like Chicago,

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:08.910
where he destroyed the
Know-Nothing Party entirely

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:12.450
without any fingerprints
using his friends.

00:44:12.450 --> 00:44:19.590
But he did so with the belief that
he needed to draw them and get them

00:44:19.590 --> 00:44:22.980
to participate in this
antislavery coalition

00:44:22.980 --> 00:44:25.370
that became the Republican Party.

00:44:25.370 --> 00:44:28.010
And until he end.

00:44:28.010 --> 00:44:32.560
As he told Owen Lovejoy, one of
the leading radical abolitionists

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:36.060
who had come to Lincoln and
wanted his leadership, he said --

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:40.760
you know the time had not
come yet in the mid 1850's.

00:44:40.760 --> 00:44:42.060
But eventually it did.

00:44:42.060 --> 00:44:44.400
And Lincoln had to wait
for the right time.

00:44:44.400 --> 00:44:47.030
And that is one of the
other things about Lincoln.

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:53.850
He steps. He says he would take
a step depending on the timing.

00:44:53.850 --> 00:44:57.330
And some people would
criticize him for being passive

00:44:57.330 --> 00:44:59.840
and vacillating and compromising.

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:03.650
But he said, I never took a step
back once I took a step forward.

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:06.390 position:56%
And in order to take a step forward,

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:10.040
he wanted to have the greatest
possible political support

00:45:10.040 --> 00:45:11.820
for what he was doing.

00:45:11.820 --> 00:45:15.240
And that was part of
his political genius.

00:45:15.240 --> 00:45:18.020
Just one more question.

00:45:18.020 --> 00:45:22.270
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much for such a
wonderful synopsis of your story.

00:45:22.270 --> 00:45:24.330
I could have listened
to you for hours.

00:45:24.330 --> 00:45:25.630
&gt;&gt; Sidney Blumenthal: Thank you.

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:26.930
&gt;&gt; You were so enthralling.

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:28.230
I am sure the audience
agrees with me.

00:45:28.230 --> 00:45:29.530
It was just outstanding.

00:45:29.530 --> 00:45:31.330
&gt;&gt; Sidney Blumenthal: Thank you.

